It was reported on Twitter that a fire alert had caused services from the station to be delayed or suspended. Transport for London confirmed on their website that the Underground station had been closed and that passengers could use their tickets on bus routes.   London Fire Brigade shared details about the incident on their website. They wrote: "Firefighters were called to reports of smoke issuing at King's Cross Underground Station. "A small part of a lift motor room was damaged by fire. A woman was treated on scene by London Ambulance Service crews.  READ MORE: John Travolta pens tribute to 'dearest' Olivia Newton-John amid death "The Brigade was called at 2215 (BST) and the fire was under control by 2254. "Three fire engines and around 15 firefighters from Euston and Soho fire stations attended the scene."  DON'T MISS:Inside Ukraine's decentralised cyber army exposing oligarchs [SPOTLIGHT]'No-one's left' Russian officer tells of mass troop desertions [REVEAL]'Atomic message' White House drenched in radioactive blood [LATEST]